{"accepted":[{"assertion":"Hosted Lean proof: plby proof of 1056 (state partial) https://github.com/plby/lean-proofs/blob/main/src/v4.29.1/ErdosProblems/Erdos1056.lean.","id":"vf_a8dbd869827c5904","trust":"signed","type":"theoretical"},{"assertion":"OBLIGATION (Erdos #1056). BANKED: explicit cut-equality certificates verified for every k in 2..14 (interval_product witnesses). OPEN: the problem asks for EVERY k; a uniform construction or proof for all k remains open.","id":"vf_ae08f178d51bb99e","trust":"signed","type":"theoretical"},{"assertion":"Erdős Problem #1056: declared status 'open'. Formalized: yes. Let $k\\geq 2$. Does there exist a prime $p$ and consecutive intervals $I_1,\\ldots,I_k$ such that\\[\\prod_{n\\in I_i}n \\equiv 1\\pmod{p}\\]for all $1\\leq i\\leq k$? Prize: no. OEIS: A060427. Tags: number theory.","id":"vf_c84f3b9237e811e7","trust":"signed","type":"theoretical"},{"assertion":"Formal-Conjectures statement: Erdos1056.erdos_1056 https://google-deepmind.github.io/formal-conjectures/theorem/?name=Erdos1056.erdos_1056.","id":"vf_fb604a52fc80a172","trust":"signed","type":"theoretical"}],"accepted_activity":false,"activity":[{"accepted":false,"banked":true,"claim":"Erdős #1056 (for-all-k) <=> sup_p M(p) = infinity, where M(p) = max_r #{0<=t<p : t! ≡ r mod p} (largest factorial-residue collision class mod p). Cuts c_0<...<c_k with equal F_p(c_i) <=> the consecutive intervals [c_{i-1}+1,c_i] each have product ≡ 1 mod p.","claimed_status":"verified_computationally","classification":"legacy_attempt","id":"vat_03ae7fa1b1b42c46","kind":"reduction","lifecycle":"banked","location":"current_commit","mathematical_scope":"partial","method_channel":"factorial-residues","method_families":[],"named_obstructions":[],"related_problems":[930,931,1056],"remaining_obligations":["OPEN: needs UNBOUNDED factorial-residue collision classes; tetrad only reaches size 5 (k=4)","the M(p) reduction + OEIS A060427 framing is the KNOWN/folklore structure, not new","Hardy-Subbarao g(p)->infinity would suffice (open)"],"source_ref":"frontier.json#vat_03ae7fa1b1b42c46","trust":"signed"},{"accepted":false,"banked":true,"claim":"attempted via frontier '?' (transfer_strength=n/a) -> no_progress","claimed_status":"draft","classification":"legacy_attempt","id":"vat_367b12740918bc68","kind":"dead_end","lifecycle":"banked","location":"current_commit","mathematical_scope":"partial","method_channel":"","method_families":[],"named_obstructions":[],"related_problems":[],"remaining_obligations":[],"source_ref":"frontier.json#vat_367b12740918bc68","trust":"signed"},{"accepted":false,"banked":true,"claim":"Deep open-core push (cross-model verified): the tetrad construction CANNOT be extended to size >=6 without new input (it is a one-seed Wilson-reflection machine, caps at the class {0,1,q,p-1-q,p-2}); #1056 reduces cleanly to the OPEN Hardy-Subbarao conjecture g(p)=#{n<p:n!≡-1}->infinity (since M(p)>=g(p)).","claimed_status":"draft","classification":"legacy_attempt","id":"vat_38f22cf876d80ada","kind":"partial_proof","lifecycle":"banked","location":"current_commit","mathematical_scope":"partial","method_channel":"factorial-residues","method_families":[],"named_obstructions":[],"related_problems":[930,931],"remaining_obligations":["OPEN: Hardy-Subbarao Problem C (g(p)->infinity) — a known open conjecture","no new unconditional construction; tetrad provably caps at 5; half-factorial sign ties to class-number parity (known/deep)"],"source_ref":"frontier.json#vat_38f22cf876d80ada","trust":"signed"},{"accepted":false,"banked":true,"claim":"SHARPER reduction (cross-model verified): #1056 size-6-infinitely-often follows from a WEAKER condition than Hardy-Subbarao — namely a favorable class-number sign h(-p)≡3 mod4 on the (proven-infinite) family of tetrad primes p≡3 mod4 dividing q!-1. Connects #1056 to class-number distribution (Cohen-Lenstra).","claimed_status":"draft","classification":"legacy_attempt","id":"vat_c41861b110fbccb7","kind":"partial_proof","lifecycle":"banked","location":"current_commit","mathematical_scope":"partial","method_channel":"factorial-residues","method_families":[],"named_obstructions":[],"related_problems":[930,931],"remaining_obligations":["OPEN: favorable half-tetrad lemma = h(-p)≡3 mod4 infinitely often on tetrad primes (class-number distribution on a thin set); WEAKER than Hardy-Subbarao but still open","Mordell/Cosgrave-Dilcher (known)"],"source_ref":"frontier.json#vat_c41861b110fbccb7","trust":"signed"},{"accepted":false,"banked":true,"claim":"Size-6 question fully MAPPED (cross-model verified): all elementary routes rigorously killed; the obstruction is genuinely a class-number sign distribution h(-p)≡3 mod4 on the thin factorial-divisor subfamily T_3 — beyond current analytic-number-theory technology. NOT a settlement; M(p)->inf is almost certainly TRUE (tetrad primes almost never stop at 5) but via non-reflection collisions with no known construction.","claimed_status":"draft","classification":"legacy_attempt","id":"vat_0f5c6ce768e52095","kind":"partial_proof","lifecycle":"banked","location":"current_commit","mathematical_scope":"partial","method_channel":"factorial-residues","method_families":[],"named_obstructions":[],"related_problems":[930,931],"remaining_obligations":["OPEN and HARD: needs class-number sign distribution on a thin factorial-divisor set (beyond Cohen-Lenstra theorems) OR a construction from non-reflection collisions (none known). 4 deep rounds: mapped, not solved."],"source_ref":"frontier.json#vat_0f5c6ce768e52095","trust":"signed"},{"accepted":false,"banked":true,"claim":"CORRECTION + concrete progress: the direct factorial-residue collision search M(p)=max_r #{t<p: t!≡r} TRIVIALLY beats the 'size-5/6 tetrad obstruction' banked earlier -- that obstruction was specific to one construction, NOT the problem. Found growing collisions M(p)=5,6,7,9,11,13 at p=17,23,71,599,3011,52163 (Opus-verified), giving CONCRETE #1056 witnesses up to k=12. Full #1056 (forall k = sup_p M(p)=infinity) remains the OPEN analytic conjecture, but it is now strongly empirically supported.","claimed_status":"verified_computationally","classification":"legacy_attempt","id":"vat_4568f4b5b745f52f","kind":"verified_witness","lifecycle":"banked","location":"current_commit","mathematical_scope":"partial","method_channel":"","method_families":[],"named_obstructions":[],"related_problems":[306,931],"remaining_obligations":[],"source_ref":"frontier.json#vat_4568f4b5b745f52f","trust":"signed"},{"accepted":false,"banked":true,"claim":"Erdős #1056: VERIFIED k=5 and k=6 witnesses at p=71 — new finite examples. Six factorials 7!,9!,19!,51!,61!,63! ≡ -1 mod 71 (7!=5040=71^2-1; 8*9≡1; 10..19≡1; Wilson reflection (70-n)! for n=7,9,19), so the FIVE consecutive intervals [8,9],[10,19],[20,51],[52,61],[62,63] each have product ≡ 1 mod 71 (k=5); appending [64,70] (70!≡-1) gives k=6. Known cases were k=2 (Erdős, p=11), k=3 (Makowski, p=17), k=4 (June 2026 tetrad); k=5/6 are NEW finite examples. Independently re-verified (direct factorials mod 71). Extends the known cases; the general 'for every k' question stays open. Novelty vs the live page comments pending confirmation before OEIS/forum submission.","claimed_status":"verified_computationally","classification":"legacy_attempt","id":"vat_612d3a4bd15d7045","kind":"verified_witness","lifecycle":"banked","location":"current_commit","mathematical_scope":"partial","method_channel":"","method_families":[],"named_obstructions":[],"related_problems":[],"remaining_obligations":[],"source_ref":"frontier.json#vat_612d3a4bd15d7045","trust":"signed"},{"accepted":false,"banked":true,"claim":"Erdos #1056: independently verified explicit prime/cut certificates for every k from 2 through 14. Each certificate is a prime p and k+1 cuts c_0<...<c_k with c_0! = c_1! = ... = c_k! (mod p), equivalently k consecutive intervals [c_{i-1}+1,c_i] each having product = 1 (mod p). Verified by from-scratch factorial-residue recomputation (scripts/verify_1056_independent.py); largest is k=14 at p=10428007. Reproduces Erdos's k=2 (p=11) and Makowski's k=3 (p=17). This is finite verification for k<=14; the problem asks for every k>=2, so it is not a full settlement. The open core is an unbounded-width extension of the Wilson/factorial-congruence mechanism (the known tetrad gives only fixed width).","claimed_status":"verified_computationally","classification":"legacy_attempt","id":"vat_55157beae49cb702","kind":"verified_witness","lifecycle":"banked","location":"current_commit","mathematical_scope":"partial","method_channel":"erdos-problems","method_families":[],"named_obstructions":[],"related_problems":[],"remaining_obligations":["scripts/verify_1056_independent.py","examples/erdos-problems/attack/erdos1056-witnesses-k2-through-k14-draft.v1.json"],"source_ref":"frontier.json#vat_55157beae49cb702","trust":"signed"},{"accepted":false,"banked":true,"claim":"Erdos #1056: no-go theorem (route obstruction) for the finite fixed-width Wilson/reflection method. In the graph on {0,...,p-1} with Wilson edges {t,p-1-t} and fixed-width edges {t,t+d} for d in a finite set D certifying (t+d)! = t! mod p, every connected component has size <= 2(1 + sum_{d in D} d). Proof: Lemma 1, F_d(X)=prod_{j<=d}(X+j)-1 has at most d roots mod p; Lemma 2, at most sum d fixed-width edges; Lemma 3, matching + B edges gives components <= 2(B+1). Hence any proof using only Wilson/reflection plus interval-product congruences of widths from a fixed finite set produces bounded collision width and CANNOT establish M(p) -> infinity. Verified empirically (p up to 27901, D={1..5}: maxcomp <= 32 = 2(1+15), fixed-width edges <= 15, Lemma 1 never violated). Diagnosis: pair-collisions can be unbounded while single-fiber multiplicity stays bounded; a proof must couple many pair-collisions into one residue class.","claimed_status":"verified_computationally","classification":"legacy_attempt","id":"vat_d6fdbba02850538b","kind":"dead_end","lifecycle":"banked","location":"current_commit","mathematical_scope":"partial","method_channel":"erdos-problems","method_families":[],"named_obstructions":[],"related_problems":[],"remaining_obligations":["scripts/verify_1056_nogo.py"],"source_ref":"frontier.json#vat_d6fdbba02850538b","trust":"signed"},{"accepted":false,"claim":"Lease expired before the pinned inventory baseline.","id":"lease:000:erdos:1056","kind":"lease","lifecycle":"expired","source_ref":"frontier.json#attempt_claims-0","trust":"signed"}],"activity_types":["attempt","computation"],"attempt_count":9,"banked_attempt_count":9,"commits":[{"commit":"121807e20b06eb8148f594dfe13e440181252b0f","repository":"erdos_frontier","source_root":"sha256:210e6e1b2ca15973f38386a512f1f8fa66bbae72bb1b9acb1daf2e669ab279c7"}],"dependency_impact":"cross_problem_reusable","detail_url":"problems/1056.json","draft_proposals":[],"edges":[{"evidence":"Lease expired before the pinned inventory baseline.","inferred":false,"relation":"claimed","source":"lease:000:erdos:1056","source_root":"sha256:540d4967071425f77c693e61f62053208b07d67667490dcb9eeef62ec3f1d316","target":"erdos:1056","trust":"signed"},{"evidence":"Accepted frontier artifact targets this finding.","inferred":false,"relation":"evidences","source":"va_06a66444891a8342","source_root":"sha256:540d4967071425f77c693e61f62053208b07d67667490dcb9eeef62ec3f1d316","target":"vf_ae08f178d51bb99e","trust":"signed"},{"evidence":"Accepted frontier artifact targets this finding.","inferred":false,"relation":"evidences","source":"va_393928a7196cac10","source_root":"sha256:540d4967071425f77c693e61f62053208b07d67667490dcb9eeef62ec3f1d316","target":"vf_ae08f178d51bb99e","trust":"signed"},{"evidence":"Accepted frontier artifact targets this finding.","inferred":false,"relation":"evidences","source":"va_4d6328e23970e140","source_root":"sha256:540d4967071425f77c693e61f62053208b07d67667490dcb9eeef62ec3f1d316","target":"vf_ae08f178d51bb99e","trust":"signed"},{"evidence":"Accepted frontier artifact targets this finding.",